                        <p>Since many clinics already have access to 2-D ultrasound machines, the developers predicted that the inexpensive and versatile device will be extremely popular once <strong>its </strong>reaches the market.&nbsp;</p>
<p>“By giving health care providers the ability to see the whole field of view by acquiring 3-D images instead of the conventional 2-D images, we hope to&nbsp;make point-of-care ultrasound more&nbsp;complete and intuitive at a very low cost,” Morgan wrote.</p>
<p>Broder, Morgan, Dahl and Herickhoff have an international patent pending on the design.</p>

